  "prompt": "What schools can I apply for with a GRE score of Q-165 V-153?",
  "response": "A GRE score of Q-165 and V-153 is quite competitive and should qualify you for consideration at many reputable graduate programs. The specific schools you can apply to often depend on other factors such as your undergraduate GPA, research experience, letters of recommendation, and personal statement. However, with these scores, you should be able to consider a range of institutions. Here are some general guidelines:\n\n### Examples of Schools:\n- **Top-Tier Universities**: You have a decent chance, especially if the rest of your application is strong.\n  - MIT\n  - Stanford University\n  - University of California, Berkeley\n\n- **Highly Competitive Programs**: Known for strong engineering, science, and humanities programs.\n  - University of Michigan\n  - University of California, Los Angeles (UCLA)\n  - University of Texas at Austin\n\n- **Selective Universities**: High-quality programs that consider GRE scores as part of a holistic review process.\n  - University of Southern California (USC)\n  - University of Washington\n  - Duke University\n\n- **Solid Programs**: These universities have strong reputations and your GRE scores meet or exceed the average admitted student.\n  - Northeastern University\n  - Ohio State University\n  - University of Pittsburgh\n\n### Field-Specific Schools:\n- **Engineering and Science**:\n  - Georgia Institute of Technology\n  - Purdue University\n  - University of Wisconsin-Madison\n\n- **Humanities and Social Sciences**:\n  - Boston University\n  - Georgetown University\n  - Emory University\n\n### International Programs:\n- **United Kingdom**:\n  - Imperial College London\n  - University College London (UCL)\n  - University of Edinburgh\n\n- **Canada**:\n  - University of Toronto\n  - University of British Columbia\n  - McGill University\n\n### Key Considerations:\n1. **Program Specific Requirements**: Some programs have higher required scores specifically in the Quantitative or Verbal sections, so research the specific program requirements.\n2. **Other Application Components**: Strength in your other application components can balance out or boost your chances if your GRE scores are at the lower end of the accepted range.\n3. **Application Deadlines and Requirements**: Be sure to check the specific application deadlines and requirements for each school as they can vary significantly.\n\nResearching programs thoroughly and contacting admissions offices for more details can help you tailor your application choices. Best of luck!",
